<div id="review_3618981609" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3618981609" />
    <a title="Al" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4995027-al"><img alt="Al" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602678997p2/4995027.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3618981609?book_show_action=true">Nov 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Al" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Al" href="/user/show/4995027-al">Al</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780199539963" href="/book/show/3963963-the-lusiads">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4995027-al?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4995027-al?shelf=european-history">european-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3618981609" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4468522944326345245">The Lusiads, first published in 1572, is the Portuguese national epic poem about Vasco da Gama discovering the sea route to India. The poem consists of 10 cantos, with a different number of stanzas in each canto, but with 8 lines in each stanza. The rhyme scheme in the original Portuguese is ABABABCC, but this doesn’t make it into English, one reason why translations are inferior. Instead, the translator of this edition managed to rhyme the last 2 lines of each stanza. The heroes of this epic ar</span>
  <span id="freeText4468522944326345245" style="display:none">The Lusiads, first published in 1572, is the Portuguese national epic poem about Vasco da Gama discovering the sea route to India. The poem consists of 10 cantos, with a different number of stanzas in each canto, but with 8 lines in each stanza. The rhyme scheme in the original Portuguese is ABABABCC, but this doesn’t make it into English, one reason why translations are inferior. Instead, the translator of this edition managed to rhyme the last 2 lines of each stanza. The heroes of this epic are the Portuguese sailors, referred to as the Lusiads, and they make it to India in Canto VII. The epic is replete with classical allusions, and this Oxford World’s Classics edition has detailed explanatory notes at the end which cover the entire epic and are invaluable for a good understanding of what is going on. <br /><br />I enjoyed this epic quite a bit, as the translation was smooth and easy to read. The only issue I have with this edition (1997) is the clumsy and pandering way that the translator made his obligatory nod to political correctness in the introduction, which I thought an egregious example presentism.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4468522944326345245" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

