<div id="review_2280682510" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2280682510" />
    <a title="Priscila Wood" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4877105-priscila-wood"><img alt="Priscila Wood" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1530460657p2/4877105.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2280682510?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Priscila Wood" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Priscila Wood" href="/user/show/4877105-priscila-wood">Priscila Wood</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/22371260-os-lus-adas">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2280682510" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer238158099177253784">(actually 2.5 stars)<br/><br/>Os Lusíadas was a huge effort made by Camões. There is no way to deny it. However, it was not an enjoyable read. <br/><br/>On the one hand, we have a Portuguese poet and writer trying to create something big and who eventually achieved it, as Os Lusíadas is commonly referred to as to the most important work of art of the Portuguese language. The rhymes, the sound, the creativity and how Camões crafted the verses make justice to the position this epic poem stands to date. On the other h</span>
  <span id="freeText238158099177253784" style="display:none">(actually 2.5 stars)<br /><br />Os Lusíadas was a huge effort made by Camões. There is no way to deny it. However, it was not an enjoyable read. <br /><br />On the one hand, we have a Portuguese poet and writer trying to create something big and who eventually achieved it, as Os Lusíadas is commonly referred to as to the most important work of art of the Portuguese language. The rhymes, the sound, the creativity and how Camões crafted the verses make justice to the position this epic poem stands to date. On the other hand, it is really hard to be in 2018 and praise all the heroic rubbish related to Portugal's discovery voyages and how perfect people were the "conquistadores" and "desbravadores". <br /><br />Portugal indeed was a pioneer on the maritime exploration for "undiscovered" (from the European POV) territories. Also, Camões absolutely wanted to emulate the tone of the previous worldwide known epic poems (The Iliad, The Odyssey), but then he praises Vasco da Gama and his likes by obviously exaggerating their deeds, raising Portugal to a God-like standard and by depreciating everything that is not Portuguese. The depreciation includes women, Islam, black people, foreigners, and so on. The racism at the time the poem was written was not unexpected, but let's be honest to say that it is a problem that, hundreds of years later, at least in Brazil, we learn about Os Lusíadas since schooltimes and this terrible aspect is not often mentioned (or not mentioned at all).<br /><br />I am not that naïve and I know this is a fantastic story, and shall not be taken as a real and accurate account of past events (the presence of gods reminds us of that), but it was not a good experience reading racist passages and to see once more how European countries invaded and slavered other people and thought it was great and heroic (I'm Brazilian and I know what they did here). Even today we are taught they did it because they wanted these other people not to be "savages" anymore (please), ignoring all the intere$t behind. I just do not have patient for dishonesty anymore, even if it is well written.<br /><br />So, even though this poem has beautiful verses and was thoughtfully crafted, and Camões (who needs no introduction) was really outstanding, this is not for me. I know that I cannot put my reality on a poem written in 1572 and analyze it as if it was written in 2018 - this would not be fair. However, I cannot put my heart on it and appreciate it entirely, as it would not be fair either.</span>
  <a data-text-id="238158099177253784" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

