<div id="review_3375041890" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3375041890" />
    <a title="Blair" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17313734-blair"><img alt="Blair" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1360462359p2/17313734.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3375041890?book_show_action=true">Jun 13, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Blair" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Blair" href="/user/show/17313734-blair">Blair</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3375041890" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1370591143858598268">A very impressive epic poem based on The Aeneid about the voyage of Vasco da Gama to India. The presence o the Roman gods, who intervene along the way, is an interesting touch, but it&apos;s also based on historical accounts and on the voyage of Camões himself, who was apparently the first European artist to cross the equator, when he replicated da Gama&apos;s voyage. A key work in world literature that I was previously ignorant about.</span>
  <span id="freeText1370591143858598268" style="display:none">A very impressive epic poem based on The Aeneid about the voyage of Vasco da Gama to India. The presence o the Roman gods, who intervene along the way, is an interesting touch, but it's also based on historical accounts and on the voyage of Camões himself, who was apparently the first European artist to cross the equator, when he replicated da Gama's voyage. A key work in world literature that I was previously ignorant about.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1370591143858598268" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
